            <biogHist>
                <p>Margaret Macintosh was the daughter of daughter of John Campbell and Mary née
                    MacAskill. She married Donald Macintosh, tailor, Baghasdail a Deas, early in the
                    1850s; the couple had at least six of a family: Flora (b. 1853), Mary (b. 1855),
                    Angus (b. 1857), John (b. 1859), another Angus (b. 1861), and Flora-Ann (b.
                    1863).</p>
                <p>Alexander Carmichael first visited Margaret Macintosh, ‘Bean an Tàilleir’, on 26
                    May 1869, during the several months of intensive song recording which he
                    undertook in the first half of that year. From her he recorded versions of three
                    long waulking songs, one, <span>Nuair reachadh tu sìos</span>, praising ‘Mhic
                    Iain Mhùideartaich na Féile’, later reordered and reworked as <span>’S muladach,
                        ’s muladach thà mi</span>; <span>Tàladh Dhomhnaill Ghuirm</span>; and
                        <span>Seathan mac Rìgh Éireann</span> [CW150/41; see <span
                        localType="mods-titleinfo">CG</span> v, 32–4]. This was the first time
                    Carmichael had heard the second ‘splendid’ song, ‘a wonderful work of word
                    painting’ [CW503 fo.770]. Margaret Macintosh had heard these songs ‘from her
                    sister who lived with her grandmother. “Fionaghal nin Aonais ic Caluim” a woman
                    who [had] a number of old poems.’</p>
                <p>On 14 October 1875 Carmichael recorded from the ‘wife of Donald Macintosh tailor
                    South Boisdale S Uist’ a charm against evil eye, <span>Eòlas Beum Sùla</span>,
                    ‘Cuiridh mise an oba seo ri m’ shùil’ [CW7/19]. This formed the basis of the
                    relatively unaltered charm <span>Obi ri Shuil</span>, ‘Cuirim an obi seo ri m’
                    shuil’, published in Carmina Gadelica under her name [<span
                        localType="mods-titleinfo">CG</span> ii, 54–5]. Another charm, a somewhat
                    unusual maleficent example printed as <span>Eoir Beum Sula</span>, is also
                    ascribed to ‘Mairead Mackintosh’ [<span localType="mods-titleinfo">CG</span> ii,
                    56–7]. In the draft contents lists used in preparing the volume or volumes which
                    would eventually come to be <span localType="mods-titleinfo">Carmina
                        Gadelica</span>, Carmichael gives ‘Mary Mackintosh, Tailor, S. Boisdale’ the
                    charms ‘Eolas Beum Sul’ (‘Cuiri mi an oba so ri m shuil’) and ‘Eolas na
                    Creotaich’ (‘Horse without power of limb’) [CW124 fo.3]. The fact that the only
                    extant manuscript charm we have from Margaret Macintosh is to be found in a
                    transcription notebook suggests that Carmichael may have taken down several
                    charms from her as field notes which unfortunately no longer survive. </p>
